</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8FD3F8D4FFB6FFFFFF1E2729FB46D173" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="C776AB5FFFB6FFFFFF1E2729FB46D173" blockId="1.[151,1437,679,1475]" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis id="F5BD774DFFB6FFFFFF1E2729FE8BD155" bold="true" box="[201,323,1346,1371]" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="00C9D0DCFFB6FFFFFD42272FFC11D155" authority="Distant, 1916" authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1916" box="[661,985,1347,1371]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orientalis">
<emphasis id="F5BD774DFFB6FFFFFD42272FFD64D155" box="[661,684,1348,1371]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="F5BD774DFFB6FFFFFD6C2728FCEFD155" box="[699,807,1347,1371]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">orientalis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="A358D6AEFFB6FFFFFCE22728FC19D155" author="Distant" box="[821,977,1347,1371]" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" refString="Distant, W. L. (1916) The Fauna of British India, including Ceylon and Burma. Rhyncbola. Vol, VI, Homoptera: appendix. Taylor and Francis, Fleet Street, Red Lion Court, London. 248 pp." type="book" year="1916">
Distant, 
<number id="7101B978FFB6FFFFFC422728FC19D155" box="[917,977,1347,1371]" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" value="1916.0">1916</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, but can be distinguished from the latter one by the tapering apical part of the aedeagus, shorter tips of styles and darker coloration.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8FD3F8D4FFB6FFFFFF1E27E2FEFCD1CD" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="C776AB5FFFB6FFFFFF1E27E2FEFCD1CD" blockId="1.[151,1437,679,1475]" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis id="F5BD774DFFB6FFFFFF1E27E2FE98D1AF" bold="true" box="[201,336,1417,1441]" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">Etymology.</emphasis>
The new species name is derived from the Latin word “ 
<emphasis id="F5BD774DFFB6FFFFFC0427E3FBE0D1AE" box="[979,1064,1416,1440]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">adustus</emphasis>
”, indicating that the body coloration is black.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
